comments.body:
There's definitely some variability in these json records, even among the 3 we have in the fixtures file. E.g. in some the subjects have types, but in one they only have labels. But I think I have covered all the known fields. The list of fields Adam sent me is below; it is close to one of the contexts in one of the fixtures, but it doesn't precisely match any of them, and none of them precisely match one another.

```
    "@context": {
        "source": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source",
        "Person": "http://schema.org/Person",
        "creator": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/creator",
        "issued": "http://purl.org/dc/terms/issued",
        "description": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/description",
        "extent": "http://purl.org/dc/terms/extent",
        "format": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/format",
        "identifier": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/identifier",
        "URI": "http://purl.org/dc/terms/URI",
        "oclc": "http://portal.getty.edu/terms/gri/oclc",
        "language": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/language",
        "title": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title",
        "DCMIType": "http://purl.org/dc/terms/DCMIType",
        "type": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/type",
        "publisher": "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publisher",
        "grpContributor": "http://portal.getty.edu/terms/gri/grpContributor"
    },

```
The list of configured index fields we aren't mapping to, because these fields don't appear to come through with the json, is:
```
          # 'tei_author_txt', label: 'Author(s)'  # mapping to author_display instead
          # 'tei_pub_txt', label: 'Publication place(s)' # in fixture data the place is part of publisher
          # 'tei_section_head_italian', label: 'Section head'
          # 'tei_note_italian', label: 'Note(s)'
          # 'title_addl_display', label: 'Other title(s)', helper_method: :ul
          # 'edition_display', label: 'Edition'
          # 'contents_display', label: 'Contents'
          # 'note_display', label: 'Note(s)', helper_method: :html_safe
          # 'title_added_entry_display', label: 'Added entry title(s)'
          # 'place_display', label: 'Place of publications'
```

Hey Trey!

Only one of those books was added to the Fondo Cicognara collection in the Vatican and is on microfiche: No 4018.

There are others but they are listed only in a handwritten  Supplement and were distributedoing amongst other collections in the Vatican library. There are currently sidelined within out project as well.

So for now only 4018 has to be included, although I appreciate the foresight that others might be added later!

comments.body:
We've talked about this before (maybe in Plum?), but I can't find the ticket. If I remember, we have two options: Either -actually- rotate the JP2 via a derivative regeneration process, or store a flag in the `FileMetadata` which will get read into the Presentation Manifest to say "rotate this image for the canvas by X", although I seem to remember from last time looking at this that there wasn't a great standard way to say the starting position - something about applying a CSS tag?

Looks like we might be able to use "Selectors" in the 2.1 spec (https://iiif.io/api/presentation/2.1/#segments), but it's not super clear how to do the equivalent in the 3.0 spec.
